To check for nitrates, I would suggest using a reliable method such as an anodic redox potential (ARP) sensor. These provide a more accurate reading of dissolved organic matter than other methods. You can find one at the lab supply store.

I understand that you're interested in turbidity. A Turbidity monitor can help you determine the amount and type of particles present in your water. The device should output a reading between 0 and 256 (or higher if you have an advanced model).

As for your temperature, it seems to be stable at around 18Â°C. This might not be too unusual given that your location is quite cold. However, it could indicate that the water is from local sources or has already been heated to a higher temperature by the time it reaches you. In such cases, you can try using a thermometer or even a low-temperature tester to check its temperature.

Regarding electrical conductivity (EC), an Electrical Conductivity (EC) meter should provide an indication of the water's electrical properties. A reading of 500 or higher generally indicates high conductivity, while lower levels might suggest low conductivity.

As for turbidity, it seems to be in its standard range of 10-20 mL/L. If you have any suspicions about the cause of your turbidity problem, you can try using an ultrasound imaging method or a water analysis.

Regarding dissolved oxygen (mg/L), this usually remains stable at around 5-15 mg/L. This is because it requires a high concentration of dissolved oxygen to break down organic materials, which in turn releases oxygen into the water. If you're finding that dissolved oxygen levels are low or high and don't seem to be correlating with temperature or pH, you might want to consider using a more advanced and sensitive sensor.

Regarding the phosphate level, this typically remains stable at around 0-15 mg/L. It can be helpful to have an idea of the potential for chemical reactions to occur with increasing levels of phosphates in your water. If you're finding that levels are too high or low and don't seem to be correlating with temperature or pH, you might want to consider using a more advanced and sensitive sensor.

Regarding ammonia levels (mg/L), these can vary depending on factors such as diet, waste disposal, and weather conditions. A higher reading might indicate that your soil is rich in nitrogen, while a lower reading could be the result of anaerobic breakdown of organic matter. If you're finding that levels are too high or low and don't seem to be correlating with temperature or pH, you might want to consider using a more advanced and sensitive sensor.

As for chlorine residual (mg/L), this typically remains stable at around 0-15 mg/L. It can be helpful to have an idea of the potential for chemical reactions to occur with increasing levels of chlorine in your water. If you're finding that levels are too high or low and don't seem to be correlating with temperature or pH, you might want to consider using a more advanced and sensitive sensor.

Regarding water hardness (mg/L CaCO3), it usually remains stable at around 2-4 mg/L. This is because the presence of calcium carbonate (CaCO3) in your water indicates that there is a high concentration of hardwater minerals present. If you're finding that levels are too low or high and don't seem to be correlating with temperature or pH, you might want to consider using a more advanced and sensitive sensor.

As for thermometer readings, if your water temperature is consistently at 18Â°C or above, it may indicate that the water has not been exposed to direct sunlight or other sources of heat. This could be due to either poor distribution or insufficient heating in your water treatment system. If you have any suspicions about this, you can try using a thermometer or even a low-temperature tester to check its temperature.

