The presence of dissolved oxygen is vital for photosynthesis by marine organisms like corals. When dissolved oxygen levels drop below 10-20 mg/L, it can lead to a decline in biological productivity and even potentially cause death for certain organisms. To maintain high dissolved oxygen levels, proper water management practices are crucial.

The presence of nitrate and phosphate contributes to the formation of nitrogen-induced eutrophication, which can lead to rapid soil degradation and even coastal erosion if left unchecked. To minimize these effects, it's essential to implement sustainable land management practices that reduce the accumulation of nitrogen-containing fertilizers.

